### Error Handling in Rust

Rust has robust error handling without exceptions. Errors are classified as recoverable (`Result<T, E>`) and unrecoverable (`panic!`).

---

### Error Handling Strategies

| Approach | When to Use |
|----------|-------------|
| `Result<T, E>` | Recoverable errors |
| `Option<T>` | Optional values (None instead of error) |
| `panic!` | Unrecoverable errors |
| Custom error types | Rich error context |
| `anyhow` / `thiserror` | Third-party error libraries |

---

### Propagating Errors

```rust
use std::fs::File;
use std::io::{self, Read};

// Verbose propagation
fn read_username_verbose(path: &str) -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    let file_result = File::open(path);
    let mut file = match file_result {
        Ok(f) => f,
        Err(e) => return Err(e),
    };
    let mut contents = String::new();
    match file.read_to_string(&mut contents) {
        Ok(_) => Ok(contents),
        Err(e) => Err(e),
    }
}

// Concise with ? operator
fn read_username(path: &str) -> Result<String, io::Error> {
    let mut file = File::open(path)?;
    let mut contents = String::new();
    file.read_to_string(&mut contents)?;
    Ok(contents)
}
```

> **Key Point:** The `?` operator is the idiomatic way to propagate errors. It unwraps `Ok` values and returns `Err` early. The `?` operator can also convert error types automatically if the proper `From` implementations exist.

codeExample:
use std::num::ParseIntError;

fn parse_number(s: &str) -> Result<i32, ParseIntError> {
    s.parse()
}

fn multiply(first: &str, second: &str) -> Result<i32, ParseIntError> {
    let a = parse_number(first)?;
    let b = parse_number(second)?;
    Ok(a * b)
}

fn main() {
    match multiply("10", "20") {
        Ok(result) => println!("Result: {}", result),
        Err(e) => eprintln!("Error: {}", e),
    }
}
